g the first book-length argument against slavery in the United States—a book so radical in its commitment to abolition that friends abandoned her, patrons ostracized her, and her book sales plummeted. Yet Child soon drew untold numbers to the abolitionist cause, becoming one of the foremost authors and activists of her generation. Lydia Maria Child: A Radical American Life tells the story of what brought Child to this moment and the extraordinary life she lived in response. Through Child’s example, philosopher Lydia Moland asks questions as pressing and personal in our time as they were in Child’s: What does it mean to change your life when the moral future of your country is at stake? When confronted by sanctioned evil and systematic injustice, how should a citizen live? Child’s lifetime of bravery, conviction, humility, and determination provides a wealth of spirited guidance for political engagement today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAuthors, Americany19th centuryvBiography. 0aWomen abolitionistszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aWomen authors, AmericanvBiography. 0aWomen social reformerszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh  awomen in history, biography, female author, self help, childrens books, slavery, abolition, activism, politics, nonfiction, spirituality, religion, injustice, freedom, literature, race, philosophy, over the river and through wood, rhetoric, anti-slavery, morality, virtue, conviction, gender, radical, opposition, enslavement.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076650940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226715858423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226715858/original  a978-3-11-076650-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a